<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-428-145  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 428 145.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  Sept 1990 v27 n9 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Teleradiology beats clock. (part of 'Just what the doctorordered', a special section on telecommunications and computers inthe medical field)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The time factor is critical in medicine, particularly in traumacases.andP;  Staten Island University Hospitals has installedPhotophones from Image Data Corp in the homes of its staffradiologists, giving their expertise almost instantaneousavailability at any hour of the day or night.andP;  Photophones aredesktop video instruments that receive medical images transmittedover telephone lines.andP;  Transmission normally takes no more than 20seconds.andP;  The radiologist can read these images with the sameaccuracy as they could the actual X-rays.andP;  An optional videointerface converts computer-aided tomography (CAT) scan images toa signal the Photophone recognizes, giving radiologists access tothe full range of imaging technology offered by the hospital.andO;With the Photophone system there is no longer a need forradiologists to make long commutes to the hospital at night or inheavy traffic, saving valuable minutes in assessment and diagnosisof critically injured patients.andP;  The system also makes it possiblefor a radiologist to consult simultaneously on multiple cases frommultiple remote sites.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Image Data Corp. (products).andO;Product:   Image Data Photophone (Computer communications equipment) (usage).andO;Topic:     RadiologyRemote Diagnosis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>